Shuffling destroys the order (the pattern) but keeps the volatility (the variance) exactly the same.

2. Signal Extraction (Kernel Variance)
The code calculates the Variance of the smoothed "Kernel" line.

High Variance in the smoothed line means there is a strong, clear trend or a distinct structural shape.

Low Variance means the line is mostly flat or jittering aimlessly.

3. The Monte Carlo Simulations
The code runs the SIMULATIONS loop (set to 40 or 100 in your script):

It creates a "fake" price series by cumulatively summing the shuffled returns.

It applies the exact same Kernel Regression to this fake series.

It measures the variance of this fake, random smoothed line.

4. Calculating the p-value and Confidence
The code compares the Real Variance to the Fake Variances.

The Logic: If the real market's pattern produces a smoothed line that is "curvier" or "stronger" than 95% of the random shuffles, then the pattern is statistically significant.

